{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567473"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:02:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:02:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19043"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19043"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.09,0.63,0.26,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11777"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98824"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11777"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19043"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81216"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1578"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"9736"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27731"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28103"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28104"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33921"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98824"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for review of her heart failure. She reports increasing breathlessness over the past three months. She can only walk 50 metres on flat ground before becoming short of breath and needs to stop. She sleeps with three pillows and occasionally wakes up at night feeling short of breath. She has a history of ischaemic heart disease, hypertension, and type 2 diabetes. Her medications include perindopril, bisoprolol, furosemide, spironolactone, and metformin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly distressed. Her pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There are bibasal crackles on chest auscultation and mild peripheral oedema.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this patient\u0027s New York Heart Association functional classification?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Class I","Class II","Class III","Class IV","Class V"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms consistent with worsening heart failure. The New York Heart Association (NYHA) functional classification is used to categorise the severity of heart failure based on the degree to which symptoms limit physical activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass III\u003C/strong\u003E heart failure is characterised by marked limitation of physical activity, where less than ordinary activity (such as walking short distances) causes fatigue, palpitation, dyspnoea, or angina. This patient\u0027s symptoms of breathlessness after walking 50 metres, along with orthopnoea requiring three pillows and paroxysmal nocturnal dyspnoea, are consistent with NYHA Class III.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass I\u003C/strong\u003E describes patients with cardiac disease but no limitation of physical activity. Ordinary physical activity does not cause undue fatigue, palpitation, dyspnoea, or anginal pain. This does not match the patient\u0027s significant functional limitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass II\u003C/strong\u003E involves slight limitation of physical activity, where patients are comfortable at rest but ordinary physical activity results in fatigue, palpitation, dyspnoea, or angina. This patient\u0027s symptoms are more severe than Class II.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass IV\u003C/strong\u003E describes patients who are unable to carry out any physical activity without discomfort and have symptoms at rest. While this patient has significant limitations, she does not have symptoms at rest, making Class IV too severe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass V\u003C/strong\u003E is not a recognised category in the NYHA classification system, which only includes Classes I through IV.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe NYHA classification is important as it helps guide therapy, assess prognosis, and monitor disease progression. Patients with Class III symptoms often require optimisation of their heart failure medications and may need consideration for advanced therapies if they continue to deteriorate despite optimal medical management. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The New York Heart Association (NYHA) classification system grades heart failure based on symptom severity during physical activity.","NYHA Class III heart failure is characterised by marked limitation of physical activity, with symptoms occurring during mild exertion.","Orthopnoea and paroxysmal nocturnal dyspnoea are common symptoms in advanced heart failure."],"references":["Heidenreich et al. 2022 AHA/ACC/HFSA Guideline for the Management of Heart Failure: A Report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Joint Committee on Clinical Practice Guidelines, 2022, https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/10.1161/CIR.0000000000001063"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81216"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19043"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"ite